  "summary": "Detective Inspector Hakast visits Mrs. Cording to investigate the murder at 19 Wilbraham Crescent. Mrs. Cording, who works for a blind woman named Miss Millechamp, explains that her typical working hours are from mid-morning until noon. When Hakast informs her that a man was found stabbed to death in the residence's living room, Mrs. Cording denies seeing any visitors that morning, stating she would not have admitted a man claiming to be an insurance agent. Hakast mentions a man in a dark suit who left a business card under the name Mr. Corley; Mrs. Cording suggests the name sounds Indian, though Hercule Poirot clarifies that it is not. Hakast notes that the body was discovered by a stenographer who had arrived at the house by mistake.\n\nDuring the questioning, Hakast asks about the clocks in Miss Millechamp's sitting room. While she identifies a grandfather clock and a cuckoo clock, she denies the presence of a silver traveling clock, a gilded clock, a ceramic clock, or a leather clock labeled \"Rosemary.\" Hakast observes that four clocks at the scene are running an hour and a half fast. Mrs. Cording adds that while Miss Millechamp occasionally buys items like carpets and curtains at auction markets, she does not usually purchase small antiques.\n\nLater, Hakast meets with oceanographer Colin Lamb. They discuss the upcoming trial of a man named Rackin, who successfully smuggled important documents out of a secure location by having them photographed. Colin explains that the operation involved a man using an identical coat to switch places with Rackin to avoid suspicion.",
